      "shortest": true,
      "solution": "def palindrome(n):\n    b = bin(n)[2:]\n    return b == b[::-1]\n\n\ndef mean(n):\n    numbers = [i for i in range(1, n + 1) if palindrome(i)]\n    return sum(numbers) // len(numbers)\n\n\nmean = mean(int(input()))\nprint(str(mean) + \" is\" + \"n't\" * (not palindrome(mean)) + \" a palindrome in binary\")\n",
      "statement": "Determine the <<arithmetic mean>> (rounded down) of <<all integers>> between 1 and [[N]], inclusive, that are <<palindromes>> when written in <<binary representation>> (ignoring leading 0's). If the result itself is a palindrome in binary representation, output {{[result] is a palindrome in binary}}. Otherwise, output {{[result] isn't a palindrome in binary}}.\n\nDetailed example with [[N]] = 4:\nIn the interval [ 1, [[N]] ], two numbers are palindromes: 1 (bin: 1) and 3 (bin: 11).\nTheir arithmetic mean is (1 + 3) / 2 = 2.0, and we round it to 2.\nHowever, as its binary representation is 10, it isn't a palindrome and the output is therefore {{2 isn't a palindrome in binary}}.",
